==Bulgaria==
On 9 October 1992, the Bulgarian president signed the Council of Europe [[Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities]], signaling a new commitment to uphold minority rights.<ref>{{cite news |author= Human Rights Watch |title= Human Rights Watch World Report 1998 – 1 January |url= http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3ae6a8a510.html |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=January 1, 1998}}</ref>

In 2013 one of the leaders of another nationalist party, [[IMRO – Bulgarian National Movement|VMRO]], Angel Djambasky was put under investigation for calling the people to arm themselves against the immigrants.

At least 6 racist crimes are perpetrated between 3 and 13 November of every year. 
112 intellectuals sign a petition to the attorney general not to register the party Ataka, which was rejected by the attorney general.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2011/05/20/1093480_ataka_sreshtu_mjusjulmanite_v_djamiiata_na_sofiia_video/|title=България - "Атака" срещу мюсюлманите в джамията на София (видео) - Dnevnik.bg|work=dnevnik.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://paper.standartnews.com/bg/article.php?d=2013-11-05&article=471190|title= Стандарт|work=standartnews.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.bghelsinki.org/media/uploads/documents/external/2013-11-13_signal_na_112_grazhdani_sreshtu_neo-nazi_partia.pdf</ref>

In October 2019, Bulgarian supporters shouted racist abuse towards English footballers during a match.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/15/football/bulgaria-england-racism-uefa-gbr-spt-intl/index.html</ref>

Discrimination against [[Romani people|Roma]] remains widespread in Bulgaria.<ref>{{cite news |title=Anti-Roma protests take place in Bulgarian city of Gabrovo |url=https://apnews.com/7ade2fc2871e40e7a7396468155a2164 |work=The Associated Press |date=12 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Everybody hates us': on Sofia's streets, Roma face racism every day |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/20/bulgaria-sofia-racism-roma-everybody-hates-us-anti-gypsy-abuse |work=The Guardian |date=20 October 2019}}</ref>

==Czech Republic==
{{Further|Romani people in the Czech Republic}}
[[File:České Budějovice 29-6-2013 24.JPG|thumb|Violent [[anti-Roma]] protests in [[České Budějovice]] in 2013]]
Roma make up 2–3% of population in the [[Czech Republic]]. According to Říčan (1998), Roma make up more than 60% of Czech prisoners and about 20–30% earn their livelihood in illegal ways, such as procuring prostitution, trafficking and other property crimes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Říčan|first=Pavel|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qtgmAAAAMAAJ&q=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&dq=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme|title=S Romy žít budeme – jde o to jak: dějiny, současná situace, kořeny problémů, naděje společné budoucnosti|publisher=Portál|year=1998|isbn=80-7178-250-5|location=Praha|pages=58–63}}</ref> Roma are thus more than 20 times overrepresented in Czech prisons than their population share would suggest.

The Romanis are at the centre of the agenda of far-right groups in the Czech Republic, which spread anti-Romanyism. Among highly publicized cases was the [[Vítkov arson attack of 2009]], in which four right-wing extremists seriously injured a three-year-old Romani girl. The public responded by donating money as well as presents to the family, who were able to buy a new house from the donations, while the perpetrators were sentenced to 18 and 22 years in prison.

According to 2010 survey, 83% of Czechs consider Roma asocial and 45% of Czechs would like to expel them from the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/cesi-propadaji-anticikanismu-kazdy-druhy-tu-romy-nechce-zjistil-pruzkum-1qx-/domaci.asp?c=A101209_161615_domaci_js|title=Češi propadají anticikánismu, každý druhý tu Romy nechce, zjistil průzkum|author=Jiří Šťastný|date=8 February 2012|publisher=Zpravy.idnes.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> A 2011 poll, which followed after a number of brutal attacks by Romani perpetrators against majority population victims, revealed that 44% of Czechs are afraid of Roma people.<ref name="tyden.cz">{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/romsky-bloger-nekteri-romove-se-chovaji-jako-blazni_216270.html|title=Romsky bloger nekteri romove se chovaji jako blazni|language=Czech|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> The majority of the [[Czech people]] do not want to have Romanis as neighbours (almost 90%, more than any other group<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|title=Czech don't want Roma as neighbours|language=Czech|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201133920/http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|archive-date=1 February 2012|accessdate=15 April 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>) seeing them as thieves and social parasites. In spite of long waiting time for a child adoption, Romani children from orphanages are almost never adopted by Czech couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/88089|title=What is keeping children in orphanages when so many people want to adopt? – 07-02-2007 – Radio Prague|publisher=Radio.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989 the jobs traditionally employing Romanis either disappeared or were taken over by immigrant workers.

In January 2010, Amnesty International launched a report titled ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur71/003/2009/en/ ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''] Amnesty International report, January 2010</ref> According to the [[BBC]], it was Amnesty's view that while cosmetic changes had been introduced by the authorities, little genuine improvement in addressing discrimination against Romani children has occurred over recent years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|title=Amnesty says Czech schools still fail Roma Gypsies|date=13 January 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114052029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>

The 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] poll found that 66% of Czechs held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref name="Pew Research Center">{{cite news|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/|title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism — 6. Minority groups|date=14 October 2019|work=Pew Research Center}}</ref>

==Denmark==
YouGov ranks Denmark as the "most intolerant" country in northern Europe.<ref name="icenews"/> 
In a 2019 study<ref>{{cite web |title=Western Europeans vary in their nationalist, anti-immigrant and anti-religious minority attitudes |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/06/19/western-europeans-vary-in-their-nationalist-anti-immigrant-and-anti-religious-minority-attitudes/ |website=Pew Research Center |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> based on Nationalist, anti-Immigrant and anti-religious minority (NIM) sentiment scores, Denmark scored a 2.7 out of a possible 10, and 25% of its population reported scores above 5.
The study also showed
29% are intolerant of black people, Jews, Muslims, Romas (or gays?). 72% rated Romas as "totally negative" while 45% had negative feelings towards Muslims.<ref name="icenews">{{cite news |title=Denmark is most intolerant country in northern Europe |url=https://www.icenews.is/2015/06/26/denmark-is-most-intolerant-country-in-northern-europe/ |accessdate=28 August 2019 |publisher=Icenews |date=June 26, 2015}}</ref> Adoptees with foreign background are often racially abused.<ref>{{cite web |title=Foreign adoptees in Denmark often racially abused |url=https://www.icenews.is/2014/12/09/foreign-adoptees-in-denmark-often-racially-abused/ |website=Icenews |accessdate=28 August 2019}}</ref>

A Jew named Dan Uzan was killed by a Muslim in front of a synagogue as part of the [[2015 Copenhagen shootings]]. His funeral was attended by the prime minister and several members of parliament and he was named Dane of the year, because he prevented additional killings by the terrorist at the Jewish institution, which has since been kept under constant surveillance by Danish police in collaboration with Danish military.

Young non-ethnic Danes have claimed that they felt that some police officers have acted in a racist manner.<ref>[http://politiken.dk/indland/ECE472795/politi-de-unge-klager-over-racistiske-betjente/ Politi: De unge klager over racistiske betjente], by Andreas Lindquist, Politiken, 18 February 2008</ref>

==Estonia==
In the mid-2010s, NATO soldiers from the U.S. stationed in Estonia as part of [[Enhanced Forward Presence]] were subject to racist attacks by local civilians, resulting in condemnations from the Estonian Air Force's commander, {{ill|Jaak Tarien|et}}, and the U.S. embassy's charge d'affaires.<ref name=Observer>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2016/02/estonia-wants-more-nato-troops-but-only-if-they-arent-black/|title=Estonia Wants More NATO Troops—But Only If They Aren’t Black|date=22 February 2016|publisher=|work=Observer|access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://estonia.usembassy.gov/sp_eng110415.html|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160328230440/http://estonia.usembassy.gov/sp_eng110415.html|url-status=dead|title=Speeches and Articles - Tallinn, Estonia - Embassy of the United Stat…|date=28 March 2016|archivedate=28 March 2016|website=archive.is}}</ref> Some Estonians, particularly from the [[Conservative People's Party of Estonia|Conservative People's Party]], voiced their displeasure at the condemnations.<ref name=Observer/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rubaltic.ru/article/segodnya-v-pribaltike/17112015-estoniya-rasizm/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160226124801/http://www.rubaltic.ru/article/segodnya-v-pribaltike/17112015-estoniya-rasizm/|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 February 2016|script-title=ru:Американский дипломат осудила расизм в Эстонии|access-date=26 February 2016|work=RuBaltic|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rus.err.ee/v/estonia/5158b28a-87cf-4dcc-aeab-2752f9801619/konservatory-obvinili-diplomata-ssha-vo-vmeshatelstve-v-dela-estonii|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225102922/http://rus.err.ee/v/estonia/5158b28a-87cf-4dcc-aeab-2752f9801619/konservatory-obvinili-diplomata-ssha-vo-vmeshatelstve-v-dela-estonii|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-12-25|script-title=ru:Консерваторы обвинили дипломата США во вмешательстве в дела Эстонии|work=Rus - ERR|date=2015|access-date=25 December 2015|language=Russian}}</ref>

The [[Conservative People's Party of Estonia]] has been described by critics as [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] and racist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e231a1618774541964fae0b226ec11e|title=Center-right party tops Estonia vote, but populists win, too|first=Jari|last=Tanner|date=3 March 2019|website=AP NEWS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yanatoom.ee/brusseli-paevik/brusseli-paevik-yana-toomiga-miks-tegelikult-koik-nii-ullatunud-on/|title="Brüsseli päevik Yana Toomiga": miks tegelikult kõik nii üllatunud on? - Yana Toom|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sotsid.ee/jevgeni-ossinovski-ma-tahan-eestit-kus-iga-meie-inimene-on-vaartus-kus-iga-meie-inimene-on-oma/|title=Jevgeni Ossinovski: Ma tahan Eestit, kus iga meie inimene on väärtus, kus iga meie inimene on oma|date=15 May 2016|website=Sotsiaaldemokraadid}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kesknadal.ee/2019/01/06/raimond-kaljulaid-ekre-programm-on-ootusparaselt-utoopiline/|title=Raimond Kaljulaid: EKRE programm on ootuspäraselt utoopiline – Kesknädal|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebulwark.com/no-not-all-nationalists-are-inspired-by-trump/|title=No, Not All Nationalists Are ‘Inspired By Trump’|date=10 May 2019|website=The Bulwark}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.err.ee/107416/conservative-politician-if-you-re-black-go-back|title=Conservative Politician: If You're Black, Go Back|first=|last=ERR|date=29 May 2013|website=ERR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.delfi.ee/a/82522277|title=Mart Helme vihakõne koosolekul: Tallinnas on plahvatuslikult kasvanud neegrite hulk. Kui neile vastu pead koputada, siis see on õõnespuit!|website=Delfi}}</ref>

==Finland==
{{main|Racism in Finland}}
Reports say that racial hate crime is a recent phenomenon, and that they are on the rise.<ref>[http://cms.horus.be/files/99935/MediaArchive/pdf/finland_en.pdf Responding to racism in Finland]. European Network Against Racism</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/news/2010/11/hate_crimes_against_foreigners_rise_2111368.html |title=Hate Crimes against Foreigners Rise &#124; Yle Uutiset |publisher=yle.fi |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref> The numbers of reported hate crimes in 2003 and 2004 were 522 and 558, respectively. In 2009, they had increased to over 1 000 (including non-racist hate crimes). Racial hate crimes have fluctuated from 858 (2009) to 641 (2012)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.poliisiammattikorkeakoulu.fi/poliisi/poliisioppilaitos/home.nsf/PFBD/AA662EFEA0162E5FC2257C1B0022E970?opendocument | title=Poliisin tietoon tullut viharikollisuus vähentynyt | website=poliisiammattikorkeakoulu.fi | year=2013 | access-date=3 September 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903171135/http://www.poliisiammattikorkeakoulu.fi/poliisi/poliisioppilaitos/home.nsf/PFBD/AA662EFEA0162E5FC2257C1B0022E970?opendocument | archive-date=3 September 2014 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the typical suspect have been a Finnish-born young man. However, over 60% of the targets were reported to have been Finland-born, although those with foreign-born parents were counted as well. The most targeted immigrants in 2004 were reported to be of [[Somali people|Somali]], [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]], [[Russians|Russian]], [[Iraqi people|Iraqi]] and [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] origin. One-third of the hate crimes were reportedly aimed at the [[Finnish Kale|Kale]], and only one in six were members of the native population.

In European Social Surveys since 2002, Finns have proved to be least racist just after Swedes. Earlier Finnish scientific data reveals that attitudes had been improving continuously for a long time.<ref>[http://www.fsd.uta.fi/lehti/fi/28/tietoarkisto09.pdf Yhteiskuntatieteellinen tietoarkisto | www.fsd.uta.fi | 2009].</ref> Professor of Social Policy and responsible of Finnish ESS, Heikki Ervasti, denies a common thought of increased negative attitudes against immigrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tylkkari.fi/ilmiot/kyokkipuheesta-poliittiseksi-voimaksi |title= Kyökkipuheesta poliittiseksi voimaksi | publisher=tylkkari.fi |year= 2012}}</ref>

A poll made in late 2011 revealed that the majority of the Finns viewed Finland as a racist country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Poll+Majority+of+Finns+see+Finland+as+racist+country/1135269860316 |title=Helsingin Sanomat – International Edition – Home |publisher=hs.fi |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref> Two thirds considered the country to be fairly racist, 12% recognised a moderate amount of racism, and 2% admitted to be very racist; 35% agreed partly or wholly to the statement "Islam is a threat to Western values and democracy", and 29% agreed more or less to that "people belonging to certain races simply are not suited to live in a modern society". One in five thought "it needs to be recognised as a fact that some nations are more intelligent than others", and 11% agreed partly or completely to "people whose appearance and culture differ much from those of the Finns are unpredictable and frightening".

In a 2018 study conducted in 12 EU member states, Finland tops the chart with the most perceived racism, with 62% of those surveyed having experienced racially motivated harassment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nielsen |first1=Nikolaj |title=Finland shamed on racism in EU study |url=https://euobserver.com/justice/143518 |accessdate=16 September 2019 |work=EUobserver |date=28 Nov 2018}}</ref>

===HSL Case===
According to a report from ''[[Iltalehti]]'', an alleged incident of racism and police brutality occurred on the evening of 4 July 2020 at the [[Central railway station metro station (Helsinki)|Central Railway Station]] of [[Helsinki Metro]]. The incident centers on two youths, one white male and one black male, who were apprehended together for not having a valid ticket. According to eyewitness accounts and unverified footage of the incident that was circulating on [[social media]], the white youth was calmly spoken to by the police before being allowed to leave, however, the black teenager was allegedly thrown down onto the floor by security staff and placed in handcuffs. One security staff member was allegedly seen pressing his knee down on the teenager's neck, at which point the victim could be seen yelling out "I can't breathe" in English, which has clearly evoked images on social media in the [[Killing of George Floyd|case of George Floyd]] in the [[United States]].<ref>[https://www.helsinkitimes.fi/finland/news-in-brief/17859-hsl-faces-accusations-of-racism-amid-alleged-incident-on-helsinki-metro.html Helsinki Times: HSL faces accusations of racism amid alleged incident on Helsinki Metro]</ref><ref>Law enforcement officers pressed a dark-skinned boy to the ground and a storm began, in which celebrities also took part - [[Helsinki Regional Transport Authority|HSL]] sees no racism in action: "The young man was completely uncooperative" [https://www.mtvuutiset.fi/artikkeli/jarjestyksenvalvojat-painoivat-tummaihoisen-pojan-maahan-ja-alkoi-somemyrsky-johon-osallistuivat-julkkiksetkin-hsl-ei-nae-toiminnassa-rasismia-nuori-oli-taysin-yhteistyokyvyton/7870880?fbclid=IwAR1dENeip7oNEn653SfN_o46hSS_wrW0knEGPC53goAeIcn8qUXvLvWWNew#gs.awy24t MTV Uutiset: Järjestyksenvalvojat painoivat tummaihoisen pojan maahan ja alkoi somemyrsky, johon osallistuivat julkkiksetkin – HSL ei näe toiminnassa rasismia: "Nuori oli täysin yhteistyökyvytön"] (in Finnish)</ref>

==France==
{{main|Racism in France}}
Jewish leaders perceive an intensifying [[anti-Semitism in France]], mainly among Muslims of [[Arab]] or [[Berber people|Berber]] heritage.<ref>{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Nickerson |title=Anti-Semitism seen rising among France's Muslims |url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/europe/articles/2006/03/13/anti_semitism_seen_rising_among_frances_muslims/ |publisher=The Boston Globe |date=2006-03-13}}</ref>

In 1998 the Council of Europe's European Commission Against Racism and Intolerance (ECRI) made a report stating concern about racist activities in France and accused the French authorities of not doing enough to combat this. The report and other groups have expressed concern about organizations like [[Front National (France)]]. In a recent [[Pew Research Center|Pew Survey]], 47% of the French deem immigration from [[Central and Eastern Europe]] (mainly from [[Poland]], [[Slovakia]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Hungary]], [[Serbia]] and [[Romania]], including [[Slavs|Slavic]] and [[Romani people]]) to be a very bad thing. Likewise, the majority of French respondents revealed negative views on the immigration of [[Muslims]] from [[Africa]] and [[Middle East]]. A small minority showed signs of anti-Semitism. Roughly 11% had an unfavorable view of Jews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pewglobal.org/reports/display.php?PageID=795 |title=Pew Global Attitudes Project: Summary of Findings: A Year After Iraq War |accessdate=2009-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216042207/http://pewglobal.org/reports/display.php?PageID=795 |archivedate=16 December 2009 }} (2004-03-16)</ref> and 8% felt that US policy was most influenced by the Jews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pewglobal.org/reports/display.php?PageID=803 |title=Pew Global Attitudes Project: III: Opinions of U.S. Policies: U.S. Image Up Slightly, But Still Negative |accessdate=2008-02-12 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211125844/http://pewglobal.org/reports/display.php?PageID=803 |archivedate=11 December 2009 }}</ref>

==Germany==
{{main|Racism in Germany}}

==Greece==
[[File:"Americans more likely to saw growing diversity makes their country a better place to live" (2016), Pew Research.png|thumb|2016 [[Pew Research]] survey of various countries, mostly in Europe, regarding attitudes towards ethnic diversity. A majority of Greeks surveyed (63%) expressed negative attitudes towards ethnic diversity.]]
[[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] emerged as a fringe movement when it was founded in the early 1980s and since then, it has evolved into a [[Far-right politics|far-right]] group within [[Greece]]. Members of Golden Dawn have been accused of carrying out acts of violence as well as [[hate crimes]] against [[Immigration|immigrants]], political opponents, [[Homosexuality|homosexuals]] and ethnic minorities. In September 2019, Golden Dawn's headquarters in [[Athens]], were closed and dissolved, only two months after the party's defeat in the July general elections.

In a 2016 [[Pew Research]] study, Greeks were found to be most intolerant nationality in Europe of ethnic diversity of all the peoples surveyed, with Europe in general expressing negative sentiment towards ethnic diversity (out of 10 countries in Europe surveyed, people who expressed a positive opinion of ethnic diversity were in the minority in all of them).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/07/12/in-views-of-diversity-many-europeans-are-less-positive-than-americans/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715014948/http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/07/12/in-views-of-diversity-many-europeans-are-less-positive-than-americans/|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 July 2016|date=12 July 2016|title=In views of diversity, many Europeans are less positive than Americans|work=Fact Tank|publisher=Pew Research Center|first1=Bruce|last1=Drake|first2=Jacob|last2=Poushter|access-date=15 July 2016}}</ref>

==Hungary==
An [[European Union|EU]] report found that legal policies that should protect people from racism and [[xenophobia]] were "not implemented effectively", and it also found that Hungarian public officials denied the fact that racism and discrimination were a problem in their country, despite evidence to the contrary. It noted that such factors contributed to the increase in extremist ideologies in Hungarian politics and media.<ref name="FRA">{{cite news |url=http://fra.europa.eu/sites/default/files/fra-2013-thematic-situation-report-3_en_1.pdf |title=Racism, discrimination, intolerance and extremism: learning from experiences in Greece and Hungary |publisher=European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights (FRA) |date=December 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-22}}</ref> The Council of Europe has also criticized Hungary in a new report, condemning xenophobia and violence against migrants and minorities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dw.com/en/eu-report-finds-rampant-racism-xenophobia-in-hungary/a-18505689 |title=EU Report in Deutsche Welle}}</ref>

2013 [[Fundamental Rights Agency|FRA]] online survey shows a middle to high level of [[Antisemitism in contemporary Hungary|anti-Semitism in Hungary]], compared to other European countries.<ref name="FRA"/> The banned [[Hungarian Guard]] and some [[Jobbik]] politicians are sometimes described as xenophobic and racist.<ref name="FRA"/>

As in other European countries, the [[Romani people]] faced disadvantages, including unequal treatment, discrimination, segregation and harassment. Negative stereotypes are often linked to the high level of unemployment among Romani people and their reliance on state benefits.<ref name="FRA"/> In 2008 and 2009 nine attacks took place against Romani in Hungary, resulting in six deaths and multiple injuries. According to the Hungarian curia (supreme court), these murders were motivated by [[Antiziganism|anti-Romani sentiment]] and sentenced the perpetrators to [[life imprisonment]].<ref name="FRA"/>

==Ireland==

During the second world war, although Ireland was officially neutral, Prime Minister [[Éamon de Valera]] was accused of sympathizing with and supporting the [[Nazi regime]] of [[Adolf Hitler]] in Germany. Following the death of Hitler in 1945 de Valera was one of many who signed a book of condolence and offered sympathies to the German Minister at the German Embassy in [[Dublin]].<ref>''An Irish Statesman and Revolutionary'' by Elizabeth Keane ({{ISBN|978-1845111250}}), page 106</ref> This led to the belief among [[Allies of World War II|Allied leaders]] such as [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] that de Valera and the Irish in general were supportive of the Nazi regime.<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Public Service Broadcasting – 1940s: De Valera and Broadcasting|work=History of RTÉ|publisher=RTÉ|url=http://www.rte.ie/laweb/brc/brc_1940s_a.html|accessdate=2008-10-30}}</ref> The substantial influx of Nazi war criminals to Ireland following the war and their acceptance into society both officially by the Government of Ireland and by the general public also lead to claims Ireland was tolerant if not supportive of the Nazi regime.<ref>"Hidden History: Ireland's Nazis", broadcast by RTÉ - January 2007</ref> 
Historically, the Jewish community in Ireland has enjoyed support not enjoyed elsewhere in Europe. (Main article: [[History of the Jews in Ireland]]).

In mid-twentieth century Ireland there was traditionally very little [[immigration]] in general to the Republic of Ireland, and hence little racial diversity, though in recent decades growing prosperity in the country (see: [[Celtic Tiger]]) attracted increasing numbers of [[immigrants]], mainly from [[Central and Eastern Europe]] (primarily [[Poland]]), [[China]] and [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]. Also the absence of colonialist baggage has meant that foreign people are not drawn to Ireland by "[[mother country]]" factors that have affected other European countries. Descendants of [[Irish people]] who emigrated in the past also started moving back to the country. Most immigrants have settled in [[Dublin]] and the other cities. Though these developments have been somewhat tolerated by most, there has been a steady rise in racist attitudes among some sections of society. A 2001 survey found that 51% of Irish people surveyed considered the country inherently racist <ref>Liam Collins. [http://www.independent.ie/national-news/ireland-is-a-country-of-racists--at-least-the-irish-think-thats-true-508512.html Ireland is a country of racists – at least the Irish think that's true – National News]. Independent.ie (2001-05-27). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> and 60% of those in the 25 to 34 age-group considered "racism" to be an Irish trait. In 2005, Minister of State for Overseas Development, Conor Lenihan famously advised Socialist politician Joe Higgins to "stick with the kebabs" – referring to his campaigning on behalf of [[Turkey|Turkish]] contract workers who had been paid less than the statutory minimum wage. The Minister later retracted his remarks and apologized.<ref>Michael O’Farrell. [https://web.archive.org/web/20120602064451/http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2005/0519/ireland/lenihan-under-pressure-to-apologise-for-kebab-gaffe-626825454.html Lenihan under pressure to apologise for ‘kebab’ gaffe]. The Irish Examiner (2005-05-19)</ref> A 2008 EU-MIDIS survey of attitudes to minorities in the 27 EU States found that Ireland had the most racist attitudes to Afro-Europeans in the entire EU.<ref>Jim Cusack. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/ireland-of-the-welcomes-is-a-myth-2133538.html Ireland of the welcomes is a myth – Analysis, Opinion]. Independent.ie (2010-04-11). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

While most racist abuse in Ireland is verbal, violent hate crimes have occurred. In 2000, a white man was stabbed and seriously injured when defending his [[Jamaica]]n-born wife from racist abuse by a group of adult men.<ref>Tim Healy. [http://www.independent.ie/national-news/four-charged-with-hatred-in-racist-attack-on-father-son-345834.html Four charged with hatred in 'racist attack' on father, son – National News]. Independent.ie (2001-05-19). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> In 2002, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] man Zhao Liu Tao (29) was murdered in Dublin in what was described as the Republic of Ireland's first racially motivated murder.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1813880.stm Murder sparks Irish racism fears], [[BBC News]] (2002-02-11)</ref> Later that year Leong Ly Min, a [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] man who had lived in Dublin since 1979,<ref>[http://republican-news.org/archive/2002/August29/29anti.html Rally against racist attacks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225105217/http://republican-news.org/archive/2002/August29/29anti.html |date=25 February 2008 }}, [[Republican News]] (2002-08-29)</ref> was mortally wounded by two assailants who had been racially abusing him.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/ireland/article7094192.ece Death of a dream as racism rears its head in Ireland], [[The Times]] (2010-04-11)</ref> In February 2008, two [[Poles|Polish]] mechanics, Paweł Kalita (29) and Mariusz Szwajkos (27) were attacked by a group of Dublin youths and died outside their home after each being stabbed in the head with a screwdriver. In 2010, 15-year-old schoolboy [[Toyosi Shittabey]], born in [[Nigeria]] but brought up in Dublin, was killed. The only man to stand trial for the murder was acquitted on the direction of the trial Judge<ref>Shane Hickey.</ref>. 

The [[Shelta]] or [[Irish Travellers]], a nomadic ethnic group once speaking their own language, have also experienced persecution in past and modern times throughout Ireland.

Recently, the Mayor of [[Naas]] Darren Scully was forced to resign on 22 November 2011 over comments on live radio about the "aggressive attitude" of "black Africans".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2011/1123/1224308000247.html|title=FG councillor resigns as mayor after radio remarks|first=Steven|last=Carroll|author2=Deeney, Lisa |work=The Irish Times|accessdate=2011-11-23|date=23 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1122/scullyd.html |title=Darren Scully resigns as Mayor of Naas |work=RTÉ News |accessdate=2011-11-22 |date=22 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123083003/http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1122/scullyd.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 }}</ref>

Ireland has some of the highest incidents of racist violence and harassment against <ref>{{url=https://fra.europa.eu/en/publication/2018/being-black-eu}}</ref> against people of African descent according to the EU’s Fundamental Rights Agency. It was joint second highest for those who said they had experienced at least one assault they perceived as racist violence in the previous five years, after [[Finland]] and alongside [[Austria]], and has the third highest proportion of those that had seen racial harassment in the previous year.

The country is one of only two in the European Union without specific race hate laws. <ref>{{url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ireland-domestic-racism-and-u-s-protests-spur-push-on-hate-crime-laws-amid-vacuum-11595434857</ref>

