[[Romani people]] have become the main target of Slovenian racists in the 21st century as the population is otherwise extremely homogeneous.<ref>[http://www.humaniteinenglish.com/article441.html Slovenia: Chasing out the Roma]. Humaniteinenglish.com (2006-12-05). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

==Spain==
{{main|Racism in Spain}}
[[Romani people in Spain|Gitanos]] are viewed with less sympathy than other groups.<ref name="Gitanos">[http://www.gitanos.org/areas/igualdad_de_trato_y_no_discriminacion/noticias/26701.html Nuevas encuestas del CIS sitúan a los gitanos como el grupo social más rechazado, mientras que un estudio sociológico refleja los importantes avances de esta comunidad], 2007.</ref>

Racist abuse aimed at black footballers has been reported at [[Spanish football league]] matches in recent years. This has led to protests and [[UEFA]] fines against clubs whose supporters continue the abuse. Several players in the Spanish league including Barcelona striker [[Samuel Eto'o]] and Espanyol goalkeeper [[Carlos Kameni]] have suffered and spoken out against the abuse. In 2006, Real Zaragoza player [[Ewerthon]] stated: "the Spanish Federation have to start taking proper measures and we as Afro-European players also have to act."<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4751876.stm Eto'o makes anti-racism protest] BBC News</ref>

==Sweden==
{{main|Racism in Sweden}}

In 1922 Sweden established the [[Statens institut för rasbiologi]], or state institute for race biology.<ref>[[:sv:Rasbiologi|race-biology institute]]</ref> The institute recommended the sterilization by force of the mentally ill, physically disabled, homosexuals and ethnic minorities, which was allowed by Swedish law until 1975.<ref>[[:sv:Sterilisering (ingrepp)|sterilization]]</ref>

According to the report ''Racism and Xenophobia in Sweden'' by the Board of Integration, Muslims are exposed to the most religious harassment in Sweden. Almost 40% of the interviewed said they had witnessed verbal abuse directed at Muslims.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/article.php?ID=2363&date=20051025 The Local: Muslims face most racism in Sweden] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118040227/http://www.thelocal.se/article.php?ID=2363&date=20051025 |date=18 January 2008 }}. Thelocal.se (2012-05-20). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> [[European Network Against Racism]] in Sweden claims that in today's Sweden there exists a clear ethnic hierarchy when ethnic Swedes are at the top and non-European immigrants are at the bottom.<ref>[http://cms.horus.be/files/99935/MediaArchive/pdf/Sweden_EN.pdf Responding to racism in Sweden]. (PDF) . Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

[[Sveriges Radio]] reported that the punishments for driving under the influence of alcohol tended to be harsher for immigrants than for Swedes; while over 50% of immigrants were sent to jail for driving under the effect of alcohol, only less than 30% of ethnic Swedes were sent to jail with the same level of alcohol found in blood.<ref>[http://www.sr.se/cgi-bin/ekot/artikel.asp?Artikel=403326 Harder punishments to immigrants] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050413053607/http://www.sr.se/cgi-bin/ekot/artikel.asp?artikel=403326 |date=13 April 2005 }}. Sr.se (2004-04-22). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> There has been evidence that the Swedish police used "Neger Niggersson" as a nickname for a criminal in a police training; this was published in Swedish media.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/17424/20090207/ Racist stereotypes used in police training] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514072116/http://www.thelocal.se/17424/20090207 |date=14 May 2009 }}. Thelocal.se (2012-05-20). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> Lately however, many incidents of racial attitudes and discrimination of the Swedish police have led for the first time to the control of racial attitudes of police students under police education <ref>{{in lang|sv}} [http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/artikel_3516139.svd Control of police attitudes]. Svd.se (2009-09-14). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> A recent research done by the Swedish Confederation for Professional Employees (TCO) found that people with foreign background have much lower chances of finding a job that is appropriate for their education, even when they have grown up in Sweden and got their education in Swedish institutes.<ref>[http://www.tco.se/Templates/Page2____417.aspx?DataID=8753 Academic immigrants discriminates in labour market] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820213610/http://www.tco.se/Templates/Page2____417.aspx?DataID=8753 |date=20 August 2010 }}. Tco.se (2009-03-11). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

In 2007, there were a total of 3,536 hate crimes (defined as crimes with an ethnic or religious motive) reported to the police, including 118 cases of anti-Semitic agitation.<ref>[http://fra.europa.eu/fraWebsite/attachments/Antisemitism_Update_2009.pdf Fundamental Rights Agency report (pdf)]. (PDF) . Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> Racism in Sweden is reported to appear within Swedish health-care services as well. A nurse at a Stockholm suburb hospital lost his job after complaining on racial attitudes of the hospital staff to patients with immigrant background. Staff was cited saying "[[Go back where you came from|go back]] to Arabia", "the patient is screaming because it's in his culture."<ref>[http://www.dn.se/sthlm/skoterska-slog-larm-forlorar-jobbet-1.960497 Nurse speaks out about racism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926075530/http://www.dn.se/sthlm/skoterska-slog-larm-forlorar-jobbet-1.960497 |date=26 September 2009 }}. Dn.se (2009-09-24). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

Swedish social services have reported on racism in Swedish hospitals as well.<ref>[http://www.dn.se/sthlm/skoterska-slog-larm-forlorar-jobbet-1.960497 Social services identify racism in Swedish hospitals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926075530/http://www.dn.se/sthlm/skoterska-slog-larm-forlorar-jobbet-1.960497 |date=26 September 2009 }}. Dn.se (2009-09-24). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> A study of statistics Sweden (SCB) reveals that segregation is widespread for Swedish immigrants when there are large differences in the fields of education, housing, employment and politics between immigrants and ethnic Swedes.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/16452/20081218/ Segregation 'widespread' for Swedish immigrants] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529065650/http://www.thelocal.se/16452/20081218/ |date=29 May 2009 }}. Thelocal.se (2012-05-20). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref> Sweden has been criticized by the UN human rights council for an increasing number of hate crimes which seldom resulted in criminal charges, when more hate crimes are Islamophobic, and homophobic, with an increasing amount of racist propaganda appearing on the internet and in Sweden's schools, for failing to provide adequate health care and education to immigrants, asylum seekers and undocumented migrants and the ongoing discrimination of the Roma and Sami minorities in Sweden.<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/23150/20091109/ Sweden slammed for UN rights failures] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111120803/http://www.thelocal.se/23150/20091109/ |date=11 November 2009 }}. Thelocal.se. Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

A study was conducted in 2011 about the Swedes attitudes to mixed marriages. The conclusion was that the views in general were favorable, but that there was a strong hierarchy based on which groups to live with. Swedes primarily preferred relationships with Scandinavians, Western Europeans and [[Southern Europeans]], and then [[Eastern Europeans]], Central Europeans and Latin Americans. At the bottom were South and East Asians, Africans, and Middle Eastern people. Older individuals and women, as well as people with less education and people who were brought up outside of [[Malmö]] (the most multicultural city of Sweden), were generally more prone to having negative attitudes. Most were able to accept family members and friends living in mixed relationships, even if they did not want to do it themselves.<ref>{{cite web|author=Text: Johanna Svensson |url=http://www.mah.se/english/News/News-2011/-Love-aint-got-no-color--Attitude-toward-interracial-marriage/ |title=Love ain’t got no color? – Attitude toward interracial marriage – Malmö University |publisher=Mah.se |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2012-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120905111204/http://www.mah.se/english/News/News-2011/-Love-aint-got-no-color--Attitude-toward-interracial-marriage/ |archivedate=5 September 2012 }}</ref>

Swedish national television (SVT) has reported on a new research done in Sweden which identifies that job seekers with a Swedish name have 50% higher chances to be called for an interview than job seekers with middle-eastern names. The research enlightens that there is not much difference between foreign-born job seekers and job seekers born in Sweden if both don't have a Swedish name; this indicates that ethnic discrimination is the main cause of the variations.<ref>[http://svt.se/2.22620/1.1795381/invandrare_kallas_inte_till_intervju?lid=senasteNytt_275216&lpos=rubrik_1795381 Immigrants are not called for job interviews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217015211/http://svt.se/2.22620/1.1795381/invandrare_kallas_inte_till_intervju?lid=senasteNytt_275216&lpos=rubrik_1795381 |date=17 February 2011 }}. Svt.se. Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

In 2012, Swedish Minister for Culture Lena Adelsohn Liljeroth was labelled a racist by The Afro-Swedish Society (Afro-svenskarnas riksförbund) because she cut up a cake in the shape of a naked African woman in public. Ironically, the cake was made by an Afro-Swedish artist.<ref>[http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/article14690952.ab Aftonbladet "Afrosvenskar kräver ministerns avgång" 2012-04-16]. Aftonbladet.se (2012-04-17). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>
<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/apr/17/sweden-europe-news?newsfeed=true Swedish minister denies claims of racism over black woman cake stunt]. Guardian (2012-04-17). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>
<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17749533 Swedish minister in 'racist cake' controversy]. Bbc.co.uk (2012-04-18). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>
<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2012/04/201241804049897269.html Swedish culture minister in 'racist cake' row]. Aljazeera.com (2012-04-18). Retrieved on 2012-06-02.</ref>

In 2015, a Swedish man motivated by racism attacked people at a school in Trollhättan with a sword, killing two.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.svd.se/flera-skadade-pa-skola-i-trollhattan|title=Tre dödsoffer: Vuxen, elev och gärningsman|trans-title=Three deaths: adult, student and perpetrator|author=|newspaper=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|language=Swedish|date=22 October 2015 |access-date=22 October 2015}}</ref><ref name="bbc">{{cite news|title=Sweden sword attack: Two dead after masked attacker strikes|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-34602621|accessdate=22 October 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=22 October 2015}}</ref>

==Switzerland==
{{Seealso|Immigration to Switzerland}}
The Swiss "Confederation Commission Against Racism" which is part of the Swiss "Federal Department of Home Affairs"[http://www.edi.admin.ch/] published a 2004 report, ''Black People in Switzerland'': ''A Life between [[Racial integration|Integration]] and [[Discrimination]]'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edi.admin.ch/ekr/dokumentation/shop/00019/00142/index.html?lang=de |title=Schwarze Menschen in der Schweiz. Ein Leben zwischen Integration und Diskriminierung |accessdate=2008-02-12 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311063519/http://www.edi.admin.ch/ekr/dokumentation/shop/00019/00142/index.html?lang=de |archivedate=11 March 2005 }}. edi.admin.ch (2004)</ref> (published in German, French, and Italian only). According to this report, discrimination based on skin colour in Switzerland is not exceptional, and affects immigrants decades after their immigration.

[[Swiss People's Party]] claims that Swiss communities have a [[democracy|democratic]] right to decide who can or cannot be Swiss. In addition, the report said "Official statements and political campaigns that present immigrants from the EU in a favourable light and immigrants from elsewhere in a bad light must stop", according to the Swiss Federal Statistics Office in 2006, 85.5% of the foreign residents in Switzerland are European.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/01/07/blank/data/01.html |title=Statistique suisse – Population étrangère – Aperçu général |publisher=Bfs.admin.ch |date=2012-05-03 |accessdate=2012-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608021414/http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/01/07/blank/data/01.html |archive-date=8 June 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[United Nations]] special rapporteur on racism, [[Doudou Diène]], has observed that Switzerland suffers from racism, [[discrimination]] and [[xenophobia]]. The UN envoy explained that although the Swiss authorities recognised the existence of [[racism]] and xenophobia, they did not view the problem as being serious. Diène pointed out that representatives of minority communities said they experienced serious racism and discrimination, notably for access to public services (e.g. health care), employment and lodging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/front/UN_envoy_calls_racism_in_Switzerland_a_reality.html?siteSect=105&sid=6382785&cKey=1137401626000&ty=st |title=UN envoy calls racism in Switzerland a reality- swissinfo |publisher=Swissinfo.ch |date=2006-01-14 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6980766.stm | work=BBC News | first=Imogen | last=Foulkes | title=Swiss row over black sheep poster | date=6 September 2007}}</ref>

In the 2000s, domestic and international institutions expressed concern about what was perceived as an increase in [[xenophobia]], particularly in some political campaigns.

Follow-up study conducted in 2018 found that 59% considered racism a serious problem in Switzerland. 
<ref>https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/directdemocracy/foreigners-in-switzerland_how-swiss-direct-democracy-deals-with-xenophobia/45803622</ref>
The proportion of the population that has reported being targeted by racial discrimination has increased in recent years, from 10% in 2014 to almost 17% in 2018, according to the Federal Statistical Office. <ref>https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/is-racism-a-problem-in-switzerland--a-look-at-the-2019-statistics/45824452</ref>

==Slovakia==
{{Further|Romani people in Slovakia}}
According to the last census from 2011, Roma make up 2.0% of the population in [[Slovakia]].

Three Slovakian Romani women have come before the [[European Court of Human Rights]] on grounds of having been forcefully sterilised in Slovakian hospitals. The sterilisations were performed by [[tubal ligation]] after the women gave birth by Caesarean section. The court awarded two of the women costs and damages while the third case was dismissed because of the woman's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|title=Forced sterilisation of Roma women is inhuman and degrading but not discriminatory|last=Kinsella|first=Naomi|website=Hrlc.org.au|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130405150900/http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|archive-date=5 April 2013|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> A report by the [[Center for Reproductive Rights]] and the Centre for Civil and Human Rights has compiled more than 100 cases of Roma women in Slovakia who have been sterilised without their [[informed consent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reproductiverights.org/en/document/body-and-soul-forced-sterilization-and-other-assaults-on-roma-reproductive-freedom|title=Body and Soul: Forced Sterilization and Other Assaults on Roma Reproductive Freedom|publisher=Center for Reproductive Rights|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>

Roma are the victims of ethnically driven violence and crime in Slovakia. According to monitoring and reports provided by the European Roma Rights Center (ERRC) in 2013, racist violence, evictions, threats, and more subtle forms of discrimination have increased over the past two years in Slovakia. The ERRC considers the situation in Slovakia to be one of the worst in Europe, as of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/the-new-roma-ghettos-000519-v20n4?Contentpage=2|title=The New Roma Ghettos &#124; VICE &#124; United States|last=Lake|first=Aaron|date=2013-12-25|website=Vice.com|accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>

Roma people suffer serious discrimination in Slovakia. Roma children are segregated in school and do not receive the level of education as other Slovakian children. Some are sent to schools for children with mild mental disabilities. As a result, their attainment level is far below average.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/roma-rights-anti-discrimination-europe-violence-eviction-education|title=Roma rights|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903151350/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/roma-rights-anti-discrimination-europe-violence-eviction-education|archivedate=September 3, 2014|accessdate=September 2, 2014}}</ref> Amnesty International’s report "Unfulfilled promises: Failing to end segregation of Roma pupils in Slovakia" describes the failure of the Slovak authorities to end the discrimination of Roma children on the grounds of their ethnicity in education. According to a 2012 United Nations Development Programme survey, around 43 per cent of Roma in mainstream schools attended ethnically segregated classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/slovak-authorities-breach-obligations-romani-school-children-2013-09-04|title=Slovak authorities in breach of obligations to Romani school children &#124; Amnesty International|date=|website=Amnesty.org|accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>

Roma people receive new housing from municipalities and regional administrations for free every year, however people complain that some of them end up being destroyed by Roma people themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pluska.sk/regiony/stredne-slovensko/zhorela-im-bytovka-unimobunky-od-mesta-znicili-zijeme-zemi-ako-psy.html|title=VIDEO Zhorela im bytovka, unimobunky od mesta zničili. Teraz Rómovia nariekajú: Žijeme ako psy!|author=|date=|website=Pluska.sk|language=sk|accessdate=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webnoviny.sk/video-v-trnave-buraju-bytovku-ktoru-znicili-romovia/|title=Video: V Trnave búrajú bytovku, ktorú zničili Rómovia|date=2013-05-02|website=Webnoviny.sk|language=sk|accessdate=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvnoviny.sk/domace/1742424_takto-si-romovia-znicili-byvanie-v-ziline?__TUU7NTQxOzAyNDUgcXFzYDhlNTYyXndhZHE=nhhjanvgr|title=Takto si Rómovia zničili bývanie v Žiline|date=|website=TVnoviny.sk|language=sk|accessdate=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topky.sk/cl/10/710436/Romovia-odmietaju-ist-do-zdevastovanych-bytov--ktore-sami-znicili|title=Rómovia odmietajú ísť do zdevastovaných bytov, ktoré sami zničili|date=2010-04-17|website=Topky.sk|language=sk|accessdate=2017-07-18}}</ref> After the destruction, in some cases it has happened that the residents receive new housing, without being criminally prosecuted for destroying state property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.info.sk/sprava/7079/romovia-znicili-bytovku-dostali-nahradne-byvanie/|title=Rómovia zničili bytovku, dostali náhradné bývanie|date=2013-05-02|website=Info.sk|language=sk|accessdate=2017-07-18}}</ref>

The 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research]] poll found that 76% of Slovaks held unfavorable views of Roma.<ref name="Pew Research Center"/>

